# Owner help — “what can I do?” / commands

When the owner asks **what they can do**, **available commands**, **how this project works**, **help**, or similar (with no other specific task), reply with a **short structured menu** — do not start publish, commit, or HTML work from that question alone.

Include **testimonials** in the menu: **`add testimonial to <id>`** (repair-linked Google review), **`add testimonial`** (standalone shop praise), **`update testimonials`** (rebuild page). Treat **`add testimonial`** the same as **`add google review`** (see google-review rule).

**Source of truth:** [`docs/owner-runbook.md`](../../docs/owner-runbook.md) (section *What can I do?*).

## Reply shape

1. One sentence: this repo manages repair stories + publish to **website** and **social** (explicit commands + confirm for go-live).
2. **Say in chat** — bullet list of natural phrases (replace `<id>` with their project number).
3. **Everyday edits** — bullets (config, images, status, batch copy in chat).
4. **After you approve** — commit / push; agent runs scripts.
5. Point to [`docs/owner-runbook.md`](../../docs/owner-runbook.md) for full steps.

Keep the menu **scannable** (~15–25 lines). If they named a project id, mention that id in examples.

## Do not

- Treat “what can I do?” as permission to publish or commit.
- Dump every script flag unless they ask for technical detail.
